      • ContextFreeGrammar

        public ContextFreeGrammar(java.util.List<Rule> rules)
        Instantiates a new context free grammar from rules alone.

        This makes the normal assumptions, more or less. It assumes the first rule contains the start variable. It pulls all of the left hand side values for the set of variables. It filters the RHS based on the objects being Terminal objects for the terminals.

        Parameters:
        rules - the rules

      • simpleCNF

        public static ContextFreeGrammar simpleCNF()
        This static method will generate an example context free grammar which is already in Chomsky Normal Form (CNF). You may wish to use this to help your understanding of how the code works, and to start writing your parser with a more simple grammar than the one in the coursework that you must convert to CNF yourself.

        In particular, this grammar generates our normal example of a context free language: 0ⁿ1ⁿ, where n ≥ 0

        The rules are:
        A₀ → ε
        A₀ → ZY
        A₀ → ZB
        A → ZY
        A → ZB
        B → AY
        Z → 0
        Y → 1

        Here is a sample derivation in this grammar:
        A₀ → ZB → ZAY → ZZYY → 0ZYY → 00YY → 001Y → 0011
        notice this is 7 steps, which is 2*n - 1 where n is 4, the length of the final word.

        Returns:
        the context free grammar

      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Produces a human-readable string for this CFG.

        We do this simply by listing the rules (much like we can construct one this way). This is not strictly formal, but it is sufficient.

        You will not need to ever convert a CFG into a string when writing your parser, but if you are creating a new CFG (as you will for part 1) you might want to print it to check what it is currently doing, to make sure you didn't make any mistakes. There is an example of this in this class's main method.

      • main

        public static void main(java.lang.String... args)
        A main method which demonstrates a context free grammar.

        The first part is a test that the code is working properly. First we generate the built-in grammar from simpleCNF(), then create a new grammar just from its rules, and assert they are equal. You must run with the -ea VM flag for assertions to work, but if you do and this assert fails, you have broken the class!

        Next, we show what happens when you print a grammar. (It prints the rules.)

        Finally we demonstrate the isInChomskyNormalForm() method, again make sure to turn assertions on, or switch this to a print statement.

        Parameters:
        args - the arguments
